# Cursor Rules — Translation App

> Short rules file. The long story lives in /docs/. Cursor's AI reads this on every prompt in this project.

## Project context (one paragraph)

This is a real-time multilingual chat app backed by an LLM-powered translation API. The chat app is the first-party client of its own translation API. The long-term business is the API itself (sold to dating apps, gaming platforms, legal/immigration tools, healthcare, support SaaS); the chat app is the distribution vehicle and data flywheel. Read /docs/strategy.md for the full strategy and /docs/architecture.md for the system design. Read /docs/roadmap.md before starting new work — phase order is firm.

## Never violate

1. The frontend never calls OpenAI directly. All AI traffic goes through our backend.
2. The chat app calls its own API the same way an external developer would. No internal bypasses. The API is built before it's opened.
3. The translation layer knows nothing about chat. It accepts text, target language, optional source hint, and a context object — nothing else.
4. Every table that holds user content has a `tenant_id` foreign key. Non-negotiable, even with one tenant today.
5. Every table with user-attributable data has a `user_id` foreign key. Required for GDPR Right to Erasure.
6. All API routes are versioned (`/api/v1/...`). New behavior gets a new version; old versions stay supported until deprecated.
7. Translation prompts return structured JSON including the translation AND the model's inferences (dialect, register, gender, domain). Never discard inference data.
8. Corrections data is append-only. Snapshot the context at the moment of correction. Never mutate a correction record.
9. Caching is aggressive. Same translation for the same (message, target language) is computed once.
10. Backend stays model-agnostic. The model name lives in one configuration point, never hardcoded in business logic.

## Always prefer

- Minimal surgical changes. Don't refactor for elegance during a feature change; refactor in a separate commit.
- Reading the relevant /docs/ file before suggesting an architectural choice.
- Updating /docs/ in the same commit as the code change that motivated it.
- Recording non-trivial decisions in /docs/decisions.md with date and reasoning.
- Storing new ideas not being built yet in /docs/parking-lot.md.

## Code style and patterns

- React 18 with hooks. No class components in new code.
- Tailwind CSS. No custom CSS files unless there's a clear reason.
- Express on the local backend; Vercel serverless functions in production. The translate handler logic should be shared, not copy-pasted.
- Supabase JS client for all database access from the frontend (subject to RLS post-Phase 2).
- Async/await over callbacks or raw `.then()` chains.
- Errors caught and surfaced. Translation failures should show a clear state to the user, not silently fall back to the original text.

## Schema conventions

- Primary keys are `uuid` from Phase 0 forward, except where current MVP rows use text usernames as IDs (those migrate in Phase 2).
- Foreign keys always named `{table_singular}_id` (e.g. `tenant_id`, `user_id`, `conversation_id`).
- Timestamps named `created_at`, `updated_at`, `requested_at`, `completed_at` (no `_date`, no `_time`).
- Enums for finite-choice fields. Don't use free-text strings where a discrete set is meant.
- Append-only tables (corrections, profile events) must have an `id` UUID and a `created_at` timestamp.
- Profile fields that can be inferred must have a `_source` companion (`'explicit' | 'inferred'`). Explicit always wins.

## File and folder conventions

- `/api/` is Vercel serverless functions (production backend).
- `/server/` is the local Express server.
- `/src/` is the React frontend.
- `/src/lib/` is for service clients and shared utilities.
- `/docs/` is project documentation. Five files: architecture, strategy, operations, roadmap, parking-lot, decisions. Don't add new files here without a decision.
- New top-level folders at the repo root require a /docs/decisions.md entry explaining why.

## AI prompt patterns

- System prompts are kept short. Static instructions only.
- User-specific personalization goes into a structured context object (~60–100 tokens of JSON), not into the system prompt as natural language.
- Every translate prompt returns structured JSON with `translated_text`, `detected_language`, and an `inferences` object.
- Temperature 0 for translation. Higher temperatures may be appropriate for other AI uses (parking lot items like response suggestions) but not for translation.

## What's out of scope (don't suggest these)

- E2EE in any near-term phase. The position is "encrypted in transit and at rest, plaintext exists transiently, never logged or trained on without consent." If a user asks about full E2EE, point them at /docs/parking-lot.md.
- Voice / audio features in any near-term phase. Parking lot.
- Cultural interpretation, conversation memory, user-controllable tone knob, AI-assisted communication. Parking lot.
- Fine-tuning. Not before thousands of high-quality correction pairs exist. Parking lot.

## When in doubt

Read /docs/architecture.md. If it doesn't answer the question, propose a /docs/decisions.md entry.
